 1. package.json
This is the most important configuration file in a React project.
It tells:
Project name
Version
Which libraries are installed
Commands to run the project
It is like the identity card of your project.
 Without package.json, React doesn't know what libraries your project needs.
 2. package-lock.json
This file is created automatically.
You never write it yourself.
It remembers the exact versions of every package.
Example
Suppose
React version = 19.0.1
Tomorrow a new version comes.
Your project still installs exactly
19.0.1
because package-lock.json remembers it.
3. index.html

This is the first file the browser opens.
When you visit

localhost:5173
the browser first loads

index.html
Inside it, you'll usually find:
HTML
<div id="root"></div>
This empty <div> is where React displays your entire application.
Think of it as an empty TV screen where React shows everything.

4. main.jsx
This is the starting point of your React application.
It starts React and loads the main component.
Usually it contains something like:
JSX
import App from "./App"
This means
"Show the App component."
It also imports
JSX
 
 styles.css
so your application gets its design.
5. App.jsx
This is the heart of your project.
Almost everything you see in the browser comes from here.
For an Expense Tracker, it might display:
App title
Income
Expenses
Balance
Buttons
Forms
Charts
Tables
When someone asks,
"Where is your React application?"
The answer is usually:
App.jsx
6. styles.css
This file controls the appearance of your app.
It decides:
Colors
Fonts
Margins
Padding
Button styles
Card styles
Layout
Example:
CSS
button{
background:blue;
color:white;
}
Without this file, your app would still work but look plain.
7. data.js
This file stores data.
For example
JavaScript
const categories=[
"Food",
"Travel",
"Shopping"
]
or
JavaScript
const expenses=[
{
amount:500,
category:"Food"
}
]
Instead of writing data inside App.jsx, it's kept here to keep the code organized.

8. utils.js
Utils means Utilities.
This file contains helper functions.
Example:
JavaScript
calculateTotal()
or
JavaScript
formatCurrency()
Instead of writing the same code again and again, you write it once here and reuse it.
Think of it as a toolbox.

9. firebase.js
This connects your project to Firebase.
Firebase is a cloud service where your app can store data online.
Inside this file, you'll usually see:
Firebase configuration
API Key
Project ID
Database connection
Without this file, your app cannot communicate with Firebase.

10. .env.example
.env means Environment Variables.
This file stores values like:
API Key
Project ID
Database URL
Instead of writing them directly in your code, they're stored separately.
This makes the project easier to configure and safer to share.

11. .gitignore
Git tracks files for version control.
Sometimes you don't want Git to upload certain files, such as:
node_modules
.env
Temporary files
Those filenames are listed in .gitignore, so Git skips them.
